title: For Sale:  Mauser 98a, Polish rework
postcontent: Predecesor to the K-98 of the Second World War. The Model Karabiner 1898a is similar to the 1898 rifle as it was a lighter, shorter version designed for cavalry, but found useful in trench fighting as well. Production started in 1905, for use by cavalry, foot-artillery and signal troops. The stock extends almost full length, with a stacking hook beneath the front stock band. The barrel is lightweight. The receiver ring is slightly smaller than the standard rifle receiver. The bolt handle is turned down close to the stock. Due to its close position against the stock, the underside of the handle knob is flat and checkered for easier grasping. This model was used in considerable numbers during World War I. After the war, many were issued to the small German Army, called Reichswehr. The designation "K 98" is stamped on the left side of the receiver. The designation Karabiner 98a was not stamped on the arm but was used in official papers in order to avoid confusion with other Model 98 carbines. This particualr one is a Polish rework, likely used in the Spanish Civil War. This is an excellent example with matching numbers throughout to include the stock itself. Strong, clean bore. Weight: 8 lbs. Length: 43.3 inches. Barrel length: 23.6 inches. Face-to-face local sales only, please.
